## Risk Rating: Low (this cycle)

No confirmed compromise from the provided IOC set. Rating reflects this specific hunt's outcome, not a statement on the organization's overall risk posture — a clean hunt result is a point-in-time finding, not a guarantee.

## Recommendations

- Retain the IOC set and re-run the sweep periodically — some indicators (especially newly published ones) may not show hits until an actor actually engages the environment.
- Feed confirmed-clean indicators back into detection tooling as low-priority watchlist entries rather than discarding them.
- Use this hunt cycle to validate/document telemetry coverage gaps — if any data source couldn't be queried cleanly for a given indicator type, that's a detection engineering finding worth its own ticket.
- Build hunts like this into a recurring cadence (e.g., weekly/monthly against fresh threat intel feeds) rather than one-off exercises.

## Detection Query Example (KQL)

```kql
let maliciousIPs = dynamic(["1.2.3.4", "5.6.7.8"]);
let maliciousHashes = dynamic(["a1b2c3...", "d4e5f6..."]);
DeviceNetworkEvents
| where RemoteIP in (maliciousIPs)
| union (DeviceFileEvents | where SHA256 in (maliciousHashes))
| project Timestamp, DeviceName, ActionType, RemoteIP, SHA256, FileName
```

